The architects saw one - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design staff since last year.
The design and architectural office Arch.Design, from whose studios a whole series of well-known Brno buildings originate, calculated from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its companies.
In wise foresight, because most of its 90 employees are aged in the baby boom and the company is keen that the project managers return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the opportunity to work shortened, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
Construction engineers have made it easier for them to reconcile their demanding profession and childcare.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of Arch.Design ’ s employees and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The operational mini-kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (grants amounting to CZK 2.8 million), the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and for the duration of 2 years qualified personnel and operations are provided.
After the utilization of the subsidies (2 years) the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue the Minikindergarten 3 further years at own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the implementation of the application.
The children are taken care of by full-time qualified personnel - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a Mini Kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but the day alternates over several children.
The kindergarten is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it concerns individual education and care, the content of the program in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable with the accompanying program of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic insights to preschool lessons, besides they also learn English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to the children.
What's more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time, thus eliminating the stress of late picking up the children from a far away kindergarten.
Parents therefore make more productive use of their working hours.
It is no wonder that natural and loyal employers are developing relationships here.
Arch.Design thus ranked among the Czech companies, which offer clear benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing through such programs.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are torn up fishmongers.
This is the Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants the house with its organic forms got the nickname "bone house".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splinters and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau by Antonio Gaudi.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colours and textures reminiscent of nature and living beings.
It is only when you look more closely that you notice that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and well-thought-out order.
During the night, the entire façade appears even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination reinforces the shine of the colours.
The same swinging lines and twisted forms dominate the interior of the house.
Wave shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and strips.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district on the busy Passeig de Grácia street no. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese executed.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally consisted of the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed with Gaudí ’ s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló house did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He collaborated with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
Especially on its drawing board the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of reality were created and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other artists and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
For example, Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí ’ s Casa Milá in the Güell Park, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given the nickname "bone house" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others again called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "gähnende house".
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolise hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces, which was unique at that time.
A bit bizarre, her 45 degrees inclination already seems.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at the time and was by no means dismayed by them.
Before the start of construction, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so appalled by the result that they demanded a remedy.
The councillors also encountered, among other things, the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no more changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the invitation to do so by the district Josep Batlló submitted an application for the letting of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewellery store.
The entire six-storey building crosses a staircase up to the roof terrace.
By the basic elements of the reconstruction all right angles and straight lines were eliminated and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of rooms.
The social part can be completely connected by the opening of the salon doors and thus a larger society could comfortably chat without having to renounce a certain intimacy in more confidential discussions.
In addition to a new façade, Gaudí ’ s renovation gave the house a rather unusual roof and two further floors.
Gaudí ’ s play with light, as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is covered and the light houses, is also impressive.
The game of these two colors gives a maximum of light to all floors of the house.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, is open to everyone today.
On the first floor the most spacious and splendid apartment is open to the public.
The homeowners decided only in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150.Birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was discovered that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, and they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price to visit the monument is however no cardboard handle, it is 16.50 euro, students, pensioners, groups and owners of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the house residents and visit him at home.
