More and more parents want people to have surveillance equipment to control the kids
The fear for their own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them by GPS.
The system, originally invented to search for cars, can indeed locate people as well, which would also help in such cases as the recent untraceable disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about as large as a cigarette box but soon it should not be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have put the case of the disappeared Anička in fear and terror, so they look for ways and means to better protect their children.
Also for the price of impairing their privacy.
"We strive to tell everyone that this is not about spying, but about an effective means to reduce the likelihood of tragedy," says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS positioning devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that in individual cases such devices can be misused, for example if you put it into someone's pocket without knowing about it, but we had no such case so far."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
However, the child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, it simply gets rid of it.
"Even very small children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they do not want to be controlled."
"At first, the mobile phones awakened great expectations among parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices," says Ms Bočková.
In their opinion, it is also controversial whether such an institution actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In the event of planned kidnappings, the kidnapper virtually always checks whether the child has any electronics with which it could be located."
"Today it is the mobile phone."
