These were the results of the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and exclusively published in The Economist.
This survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995, indicating the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year's September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and, secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased strongly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been growing by about 6% annually since 2002, the number of advocates for democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Even in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since last year ’ s sharp collapse, such a trend can be seen.
But only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region ’ s most populous countries, are convinced Democrats, lowering the regional average (see chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country ’ s democratic practice, which is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (diagram 3).
Approximately 34% trust the congress of their country and 45% trust their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America ’ s economic crises undermined efforts for more democracy.
This continued during the global economic crisis, perhaps because the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught up by a stronger social net.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only marginally in 2009 and fell by 32% again this year.)
But there are strong mood differences from country to country (see chart 4).
Brazil ’ s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more palpable and violent crimes have increased, this is less the case.
Only for the second time since the start of the survey, many respondents in Latin America see a greater problem in their country than in unemployment (see diagram 5).
Approximately 31% say that either they themselves or a family member were victims of a crime last year. However, compared to 38% last year, the levels have fallen, reaching the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in the stronger support of the private and market economies: about 71% of respondents above the region stated that the private sector is essential for development, and in 2007 it was 56% (see chart 6).
Approximately 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared with 47% last year.
