The discovery of a foreign bacterial species, which can live among other things by arsenic, opens up new possibilities for new forms of life on earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is in their view a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"He needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"This makes it something very special, although it is almost a kind of 'alien' form of life," said Paul C.W. Davies from Arizona State University and Co-author of the report, which will be published in the online journal Science on Thursday.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But, as the scientists discovered, the bacterium in Mono Lake in California continues to grow even if it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"One wonders what else is possible," said the co-author of the Ariel D. Anbar report from Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for alien life, since scientists must recognize life and its forms, so Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details of the discovery were disclosed gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements, and that the 'standard elements', which are in our opinion absolutely vital, are not necessarily specified", said Charles Cockell, Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novelty, because it shows that one element can be replaced by another in basic biochemical processes and structures," added Cockell.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe and Simon from NASA ’ s Astrobiological Institute, who conducted the study, chose Mono Lake due to its high arsenic content.
As arsenic and phosphorus are chemically identical, they assumed that microbes exposed to both may replace one element with the other.
"The toxicity of the arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently than phosphorus. It gets into our biochemical system, where it almost smears everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ1 to an increasing arsenic concentration. It adapted and grew.
The microbe grows better in phosphorus, but that it can also survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based form of life can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, on which arsenic occurs more frequently.
According to Jamie S. Foster, lecturer in microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but there has not been a working example yet.
Arsen was more common in the early earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms have used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have developed differently from the early age of the Earth," said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe Netanyahu's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
