Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin has chosen to retain the euro, but at the same time has established conditions for the whole of the European Union.
Tensions in the markets have triggered a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has put forward new adjustment measures, starting with tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, the regulation of temporary workers or the lifting of the 426 euro support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, up to the privatisation of 49% of AENA, the management of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former president Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as the person responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
Let us anticipate that Merkel ’ s position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany takes a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German mark - although this sounds more like science fiction - supported by a large majority of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a reorganisation of the euro in accordance with German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of the countries that exceed the requirements; possible suspension of payments by some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission provided incentives for deficits, and the German government withdrew a constitutional reform to prevent it from 2016.
This was the first sign of the divergence between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully ousted the decision to save Greece.
That was strongly criticised at the time, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, public opinion and published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel comes out anew with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union ’ s agreements to enable a country to be saved while, at the same time, obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it boosted the Irish crisis and all the following.
But their proposal, albeit somewhat sweetened, has been adopted, and in the next few months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to exceed it.
It says to everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, there will no longer be the old functioning of the euro from that date.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the infringing countries will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent, and in this case the private sector will have to pay part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to take a hard course of growth, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as Spain has cited in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not understand it.
It is not just a question of cutting the government deficit down to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will turn into more calm.
And that we will make use of the opportunities offered by us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero has also understood this, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in one ’ s own house has paved the way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it does not look like this would change.
Among the possibilities envisaged, we should not exclude the fact that we have to leave the euro area, which is full of little reputable countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sport and control bypass
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The elimination in the match of 23 November against the Ajax in the Champions League, allegedly instigated by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos), led to a lot of ink being spilled over whether it was an unsporting action or not and whether both players might be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and as the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will fulfil the mandatory penalty on the next league match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, UEFA ’ s disciplinary committee punished the coach of the club, José Moreover, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten, but in this sport obeyed rules.
Part of the debate about the case depicted is based on the fact that a team of the football club Real Madrid (who in his anthem pretends nobility and honor and on other occasions had punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role, and on the dramatization of the club, who added an episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is not explicitly prohibited by the Statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts constitute a rule circumvention. Indeed, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to bypass its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused by the spirit of the sport should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the infringing players draw an unjustified benefit from the opposite.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by mismatch or rule circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was not secretly carried out to avoid a sanction, but should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and joyfully accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the infringer drew from the intentional fouls.
Here it should be stressed that the rival was neither brought into an unfavourable position nor were advantages for the played game required, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it ’ s a long-term advantage, up to a certain degree of ignorance, as the team could eventually leave. Furthermore, players get a sanction with this approach and pass into the second cycle of cards, in which they excrete less than in the first cycle due to a card accumulation.
So it is not so clear whether it is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the sporting spirit, which also includes strategic decisions to maximise the benefits of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to bypass sanction (that would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they rather wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision to evade or flee without punishment.
Although the border between invention and regulatory environment has been blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the polemic arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked transmission of rules.
The damage caused by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than aesthetic.
