The US changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Before they talk to the consulate, people must present themselves to the visa application services; costs will be shortened.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa will change in the United States Embassy and consulates.
In the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the visa application services (ASC, the initial letters in English) prior to their consultation in the consulate.
The staff of the ASC takes up the biometric data of the applicant, which are checked by the consulate before the interview.
The new method has certain advantages for aspirants, including:
The total cost of handling the visa is reduced, because it is no longer necessary to pay separately the appointment agreement, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed out.
The applicant makes only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not have to talk to the consulate, they only have to imagine the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and take their fingerprints.
Since the biometric data are collected in the ASC, the applicants who need a second date for the consultation will have less time there than before.
Those who apply for a visa to the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, see http: / / mexico.usembassy.gov / boletines / sp101201 _ Visas / FAQs.html
