Global Plan for Renewal of Lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (CFCs), which is almost a third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved in order to stabilise the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete large-scale projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of compulsory reduction obligations of the developed countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of the CFCs released on earth due to lighting, if the white-annealed bulbs, which still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or even better by light-emitting diodes (LED).
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emission emitters such as the United States, China, Europe, and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFCs emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt would still have to be deducted from this balance sheet in order to stabilise the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020, in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-annealed bulbs 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced by twice as much.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last between 6000 to 10,000 hours on average.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those brought on the market by Philips this week - this company, incidentally, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-annealed bulb, indicating the savings of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that iese completely novel light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also function with a control resistance.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except for producers providing a collection point.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not compact fluorescent bulbs, but rather coal-fired power stations that emit much more mercury to generate electricity wasted by the bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power stations emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would make thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save a billion dollars per year in the purchase of electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power stations, whose construction would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
